# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: systemverilog
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions can help a programmer read the code, help a compiler compile it, or help the program detect its own defects.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] For the latter, some programs check assertions by actually evaluating the predicate as they run.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Then, if it is not in fact true – an assertion failure – the program considers itself to be broken and typically deliberately crashes or throws an assertion failure exception.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Programmers can use assertions to help specify programs and to reason about program correctness.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] For example, a precondition—an assertion placed at the beginning of a section of code—determines the set of states under which the programmer expects the code to execute.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] A postcondition—placed at the end—describes the expected state at the end of execution.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The example above uses the notation for including assertions used by C.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] That notation cannot be used in existing mainstream programming languages.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] However, programmers can include unchecked assertions using the comment feature of their programming language.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The braces included in the comment help distinguish this use of a comment from other uses.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Libraries may provide assertion features as well.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Several modern programming languages include checked assertions – statements that are checked at runtime or sometimes statically.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] If an assertion evaluates to false at runtime, an assertion failure results, which typically causes execution to abort.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This draws attention to the location at which the logical inconsistency is detected and can be preferable to the behaviour that would otherwise result.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The use of assertions helps the programmer design, develop, and reason about a program.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In languages such as Eiffel, assertions form part of the design process; other languages, such as C and Java, use them only to check assumptions at runtime.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In both cases, they can be checked for validity at runtime, but can usually also be suppressed.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions can function as a form of documentation: they can describe the state the code expects to find before it runs (its preconditions), and the state the code expects to result in when it is finished running (postconditions); they can also specify invariants of a class.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Eiffel integrates such assertions into the language and automatically extracts them to document the class.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This forms an important part of the method of design by contract.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This approach is also useful in languages that do not explicitly support it: the advantage of using assertion statements rather than assertions in comments is that the program can check the assertions every time it runs; if the assertion no longer holds, an error can be reported.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This prevents the code from getting out of sync with the assertions.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] For example, the following demonstrates design by contract in C++ (using C++26 contracts).
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] An assertion may be used to verify that an assumption made by the programmer during the implementation of the program remains valid when the program is executed.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In Java, `%` is the *remainder* operator (*modulo*), and in Java, if its first operand is negative, the result can also be negative (unlike the modulo used in mathematics).
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer has assumed that `total` is non-negative, so that the remainder of a division by 2 will always be 0 or 1.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The assertion makes this assumption explicit: if `countNumberOfUsers` does return a negative value, the program may have a bug.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] A major advantage of this technique is that when an error does occur, it is detected immediately and directly, rather than later through often obscure effects.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Since an assertion failure usually reports the code location, one can often pinpoint the error without further debugging.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions are also sometimes placed at points where the execution is not supposed to reach.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] For example, assertions could be placed at the `default` clause of the `switch` statement in languages such as C, C++, and Java.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Any case that the programmer does not handle intentionally will raise an error, and the program will abort rather than silently continuing in an erroneous state.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In D such an assertion is added automatically when a `switch` statement doesn't contain a `default` clause.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In Java, assertions have been a part of the language since version 1.4.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertion failures result in raising an `AssertionError` when the program is run with the appropriate flags, without which the assert statements are ignored.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In C, they are added on by the standard header `<assert.h>` defining `assert(*assertion*)` as a macro that signals an error in the case of failure, usually terminating the program.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In C++, both `<assert.h>` and `<cassert>` headers provide the `assert` macro.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The danger of assertions is that they may cause side effects either by changing memory data or by changing thread timing.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions should be implemented carefully, so they cause no side effects on program code.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertion constructs in a language allow for easy test-driven development (TDD) without the use of a third-party library.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In C#, there is no assertion macro or keyword, but instead classes `System.Diagnostics.Debug` and `System.Diagnostics.Trace` which provide `Assert()` methods.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] During the development cycle, the programmer will typically run the program with assertions enabled.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] When an assertion failure occurs, the programmer is immediately notified of the problem.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Many assertion implementations will also halt the program's execution: this is useful, since if the program continued to run after an assertion violation occurred, it might corrupt its state and make the cause of the problem more difficult to locate.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Using the information provided by the assertion failure (such as the location of the failure and perhaps a stack trace, or even the full program state if the environment supports core dumps or if the program is running in a debugger), the programmer can usually fix the problem.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Thus, assertions provide a very powerful tool in debugging.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] When a program is deployed to production, assertions are typically turned off to avoid any overhead or side effects they may have.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In some cases, assertions are completely absent from deployed code, such as in C/C++ assertions via macros.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In other cases, such as Java, assertions are present in the deployed code and can be turned on in the field for debugging.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions may also be used to promise the compiler that a given edge condition is not actually reachable, thereby permitting certain optimizations that would not otherwise be possible.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In this case, disabling the assertions could actually reduce performance.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions that are checked at compile time are called static assertions.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Static assertions are particularly useful in compile-time template metaprogramming, but can also be used in low-level languages like C by introducing illegal code if (and only if) the assertion fails.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] C11 and C++11 support static assertions directly through `static_assert`.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because the compiler will not allow two case labels with the same constant.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int)==4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This construct does not work at file scope (i.e., not inside a function), and so it must be wrapped inside a function.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] If the `(BOOLEAN CONDITION)` part evaluates to false, then the above code will not compile because arrays may not have a negative length.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] If, in fact, the compiler allows a negative length, then the initialization byte (the `'!'` part) should cause even such over-lenient compilers to complain.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The Boolean expression must be a compile-time constant value, for example `(sizeof(int) == 4)` would be a valid expression in that context.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Both of these methods require a method of constructing unique names.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers support a `__COUNTER__` preprocessor define that facilitates the construction of unique names, by returning monotonically increasing numbers for each compilation unit.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] D provides static assertions through the use of `static assert`.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Most languages allow assertions to be enabled or disabled globally, and sometimes independently.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions are often enabled during development and disabled during final testing and on release to the customer.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Not checking assertions avoids the cost of evaluating the assertions while (assuming the assertions are free of side effects) still producing the same result under normal conditions.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Under abnormal conditions, disabling assertion checking can mean that a program that would have aborted will continue to run.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Some languages, including C, YASS, and C++, can completely remove assertions at compile time using the preprocessor.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Similarly, launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Java requires an option to be passed to the run-time engine in order to *enable* assertions.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Absent the option, assertions are bypassed, but they always remain in the code unless optimised away by a JIT compiler at run-time or excluded at compile time via the programmer manually placing each assertion behind an `if (false)` clause.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Programmers can build checks into their code that are always active by bypassing or manipulating the language's normal assertion-checking mechanisms.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions are distinct from routine error-handling.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions document logically impossible situations and discover programming errors: if the impossible occurs, then something fundamental is clearly wrong with the program.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This is distinct from error handling: most error conditions are possible, although some may be extremely unlikely to occur in practice.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Using assertions as a general-purpose error handling mechanism is unwise: assertions do not allow for recovery from errors; an assertion failure will normally halt the program's execution abruptly; and assertions are often disabled in production code.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Assertions also do not display a user-friendly error message.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Here, the programmer is aware that `malloc` will return a `NULL` pointer if memory is not allocated.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This is possible: the operating system does not guarantee that every call to `malloc` will succeed.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] If an out-of-memory error occurs, the program will immediately abort.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Without the assertion, the program would continue running until `ptr` was dereferenced, and possibly longer, depending on the specific hardware being used.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] So long as assertions are not disabled, an immediate exit is assured.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] But if a graceful failure is desired, the program has to handle the failure.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] For example, a server may have multiple clients, or may hold resources that will not be released cleanly, or it may have uncommitted changes to write to a datastore.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In such cases, it is better to fail a single transaction than to abort abruptly.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Another error is to rely on the side effects of expressions used as arguments of an assertion.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] One should always keep in mind that assertions might not be executed at all, since their sole purpose is to verify that a condition which should always be true does, in fact, hold true.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Consequently, if the program is considered to be error-free and released, assertions may be disabled and will no longer be evaluated.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This might look like a smart way to assign the return value of `malloc` to `ptr` and check if it is `NULL` in one step, but the `malloc` call and the assignment to `ptr` is a side effect of evaluating the expression that forms the `assert` condition.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] When the `NDEBUG` parameter is passed to the compiler, as when the program is considered to be error-free and released, the `assert()` statement is removed, so `malloc()` isn't called, rendering `ptr` uninitialised.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] This could potentially result in a segmentation fault or similar null pointer error much further down the line in program execution, causing bugs that may be sporadic and/or difficult to track down.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Programmers sometimes use a similar VERIFY(X) define to alleviate this problem.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Modern compilers may issue a warning when encountering the above code.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] Furthermore, we may, at such a point, indicate the validity of these limitations.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] The assertional method for proving the correctness of programs was advocated by Alan Turing.
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In a talk "Checking a Large Routine" at Cambridge, June 24, 1949, Turing suggested: "How can one check a large routine in the sense of making sure that it's right?
[src:systemverilog/assertion-software-development] In order that the man who checks may not have too difficult a task, the programmer should make a number of definite *assertions* which can be checked individually, and from which the correctness of the whole program easily follows".
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In computer engineering, a **hardware description language** (**HDL**) is a specialized computer language used to describe the structure and behavior of electronic circuits, usually to design application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) and to program field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language enables a precise, formal description of an electronic circuit that allows for the automated analysis and simulation of the circuit.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] It also allows for the synthesis of an HDL description into a netlist (a specification of physical electronic components and how they are connected together), which can then be placed and routed to produce the set of masks used to create an integrated circuit.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A hardware description language looks much like a programming language such as C or ALGOL; it is a textual description consisting of expressions, statements and control structures.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] One important difference between most programming languages and HDLs is that HDLs explicitly include the notion of time.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDLs form an integral part of electronic design automation (EDA) systems, especially for complex circuits, such as application-specific integrated circuits, microprocessors, and programmable logic devices.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDLs were created to implement register-transfer level abstraction, a model of the dataflow and timing of a circuit.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Two major hardware description languages exist: VHDL and Verilog.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In them, three different types of description occur: *dataflow*, *behavioral*, and *structural*.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDLs are standard text-based expressions of the structure of electronic systems and their behaviour over time.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Like concurrent programming languages, HDL syntax and semantics include explicit notations for expressing concurrency.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] However, in contrast to most software programming languages, HDLs also include an explicit notion of time, which is a primary attribute of hardware.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Languages whose only characteristic is to express circuit connectivity between a hierarchy of blocks are properly classified as netlist languages used in electric computer-aided design.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDL can be used to express designs in structural, behavioral or register-transfer-level architectures for the same circuit functionality; in the latter two cases the synthesizer decides the architecture and logic gate layout.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDLs are used to write executable specifications for hardware.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A program designed to implement the underlying semantics of the language statements and simulate the progress of time provides the hardware designer with the ability to model a piece of hardware before it is created physically.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] It is this executability that gives HDLs the illusion of being programming languages, when they are more precisely classified as specification languages or modeling languages.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Simulators capable of supporting discrete-event (digital) and continuous-time (analog) modeling exist, and HDLs targeted for each are available.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] It is certainly possible to represent hardware semantics using traditional programming languages such as C++, which operate on control flow semantics in contrast to dataflow, although to function as such, programs must be augmented with extensive and unwieldy class libraries.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Generally, however, software programming languages include no ability to express time explicitly, and thus cannot function as hardware description languages.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Before the debut of System Verilog in 2002, C++ integration with a logic simulator was one of the few ways to use object-oriented programming in hardware verification.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] System Verilog is the first major HDL to offer object-orientation and garbage collection.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Using the proper subset of hardware description language, a program called a synthesizer, or logic synthesis tool, can infer hardware logic operations from the language statements and produce an equivalent netlist of generic hardware primitives to implement the specified behaviour.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Synthesizers generally ignore the expression of any timing constructs in the text.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Digital logic synthesizers, for example, generally use clock edges as the way to time the circuit, ignoring any timing constructs.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The ability to have a synthesizable subset of the language does not itself make a hardware description language.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The first hardware description languages appeared in the late 1960s, looking like more traditional languages.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The first that had a lasting effect was described in 1971 in C.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Gordon Bell and Allen Newell's text *Computer Structures*.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] This text introduced the concept of register transfer level, first used in the ISP language to describe the behavior of the Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) PDP-8.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The language became more widespread with the introduction of DEC's PDP-16 RT-Level Modules (RTMs) and a book describing their use.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] At least two implementations of the basic ISP language (ISPL and ISPS) followed.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] ISPS was well suited to describe relations between the inputs and the outputs of the design and was quickly adopted by commercial teams at DEC, and by several research teams in the US and among its allies in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The RTM products never succeeded commercially and DEC stopped marketing them in the mid-1980s, as new methods grew more popular, more so very-large-scale integration (VLSI).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Separate work done about 1979 at the University of Kaiserslautern produced a language named *KAiserslautern Register Transfer Language* (KARL), which included design calculus language features supporting VLSI chip floorplanning and structured hardware design.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] This work was also the basis of KARL's interactive graphic sister language ABL, whose name was an initialism for "a block diagram language".
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] ABL was implemented in the early 1980s by the Centro Studi e Laboratori Telecomunicazioni (CSELT) in Torino, Italy, producing the ABLED graphic VLSI design editor.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In the mid-1980s, a VLSI design framework was implemented around KARL and ABL by an international consortium funded by the Commission of the European Union.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] By the late 1970s, design using programmable logic devices (PLDs) became popular, although these designs were primarily limited to designing finite-state machines.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The work at Data General in 1980 used these same devices to design the Data General Eclipse MV/8000, and commercial need began to grow for a language that could map well to them.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] By 1983 Data I/O introduced ABEL to fill that need.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In 1985, as design shifted to VLSI, Gateway Design Automation introduced Verilog, and Intermetrics released the first completed version of the VHSIC Hardware Description Language (VHDL).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] VHDL was developed at the behest of the United States Department of Defense's Very High Speed Integrated Circuit Program (VHSIC), and was based on the Ada programming language, and on the experience gained with the earlier development of ISPS.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Initially, Verilog and VHDL were used to document and simulate circuit designs already captured and described in another form (such as schematic files).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDL simulation enabled designers to work at a higher level of abstraction than simulation at the schematic level, and thus increased design capacity from hundreds of transistors to thousands.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In 1986, with the support of the U.S Department of Defense, VHDL was sponsored as an IEEE standard (IEEE Std 1076), and the first IEEE-standardized version of VHDL, IEEE Std 1076-1987, was approved in December 1987.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Cadence Design Systems later acquired Gateway Design Automation for the rights to Verilog-XL, the HDL simulator that would become the de facto standard of Verilog simulators for the next decade.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The introduction of logic synthesis for HDLs pushed HDLs from the background into the foreground of digital design.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Synthesis tools compiled HDL source code files (written in a constrained format named RTL) into a manufacturable netlist description in terms of logic gates and transistors.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Writing synthesizable RTL files required practice and discipline on the part of the designer; compared to a traditional schematic layout, synthesized RTL netlists were almost always larger in area and slower in performance.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Within a few years, VHDL and Verilog emerged as the dominant HDLs in the electronics industry, while older and less capable HDLs gradually disappeared from use.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] However, VHDL and Verilog share many of the same limits, such as being unsuitable for analog or mixed-signal circuit simulation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Specialized HDLs (such as Confluence) were introduced with the explicit goal of fixing specific limits of Verilog and VHDL, though none were ever intended to replace them.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Over the years, much effort has been invested in improving HDLs.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The latest iteration of Verilog, formally named IEEE 1800-2005 SystemVerilog, introduces many new features (classes, random variables, and properties/assertions) to address the growing need for better test bench randomization, design hierarchy, and reuse.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A future revision of VHDL is also in development, and is expected to match SystemVerilog's improvements.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] As a result of the efficiency gains realized using HDL, a majority of modern digital circuit design revolves around it.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Most designs begin as a set of requirements or a high-level architectural diagram.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Control and decision structures are often prototyped in flowchart applications, or entered in a editor.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The process of writing the HDL description is highly dependent on the nature of the circuit and the designer's preference for coding style.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The HDL is merely the 'capture language', often beginning with a high-level algorithmic description such as a C++ mathematical model.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Designers often use scripting languages such as Perl to automatically generate repetitive circuit structures in the HDL language.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Special text editors offer features for automatic indentation, syntax-dependent coloration, and macro-based expansion of the entity/architecture/signal declaration.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The HDL code then undergoes a code review, or auditing.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In preparation for synthesis, the HDL description is subject to an array of automated checkers.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The checkers report deviations from standardized code guidelines, identify potential ambiguous code constructs before they can cause misinterpretation, and check for common logical coding errors, such as floating ports or shorted outputs.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] This process aids in resolving errors before the code is synthesized.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In industry parlance, HDL design generally ends at the synthesis stage.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Once the synthesis tool has mapped the HDL description into a gate netlist, the netlist is passed off to the back-end stage.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Depending on the physical technology (FPGA, ASIC gate array, ASIC standard cell), HDLs may or may not play a significant role in the back-end flow.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In general, as the design flow progresses toward a physically realizable form, the design database becomes progressively more laden with technology-specific information, which cannot be stored in a generic HDL description.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Finally, an integrated circuit is manufactured or programmed for use.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Essential to HDL design is the ability to simulate HDL programs.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Simulation allows an HDL description of a design (called a model) to pass design verification, an important milestone that validates the design's intended function (specification) against the code implementation in the HDL description.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] It also permits architectural exploration.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A designer can experiment with design choices by writing multiple variations of a base design, then comparing their behavior in simulation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Thus, simulation is critical for successful HDL design.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] To simulate an HDL model, a designer writes a top-level simulation environment (called a test bench).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] At minimum, a testbench contains an instantiation of the model (called the device under test or DUT), pin/signal declarations for the model's input/output (I/O), and a clock waveform.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The testbench code is event driven: a designer writes HDL statements to implement the (testbench-generated) reset-signal, to model interface transactions (such as a host–bus read/write), and to monitor the DUT's output.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] An HDL simulator — the program that executes the testbench — maintains the simulator clock, which is the master reference for all events in the testbench simulation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Events occur only at the instants dictated by the testbench HDL (such as a reset-toggle coded into the testbench), or in reaction (by the model) to stimulus and triggering events.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Modern HDL simulators have full-featured graphical user interfaces, complete with a suite of debug tools.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] These allow the user to stop and restart the simulation at any time, insert simulator breakpoints (independent of the HDL code), and monitor or modify any element in the HDL model hierarchy.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Modern simulators can also link the HDL environment to user-compiled libraries, through a defined PLI/VHPI interface.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Linking is system-dependent (x86, SPARC etc. running Windows/Linux/Solaris), as the HDL simulator and user libraries are compiled and linked outside the HDL environment.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Design verification is often the most time-consuming portion of the design process, due to the disconnect between a device's functional specification, the designer's interpretation of the specification, and the imprecision of the HDL language.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Most of the initial test/debug cycle is conducted in the HDL *simulator* environment, as the early stage of the design is subject to frequent and major circuit changes.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] An HDL description can also be prototyped and tested in hardware — programmable logic devices are often used for this purpose.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Hardware prototyping is comparatively more expensive than HDL simulation, but offers a real-world view of the design.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Prototyping is the best way to check interfacing against other hardware devices and hardware prototypes.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Even those running on slow FPGAs offer much shorter simulation times than pure HDL simulation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Historically, design verification was a laborious, repetitive loop of writing and running simulation test cases against the design under test.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] As chip designs have grown larger and more complex, the task of design verification has grown to the point where it now dominates the schedule of a design team.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Looking for ways to improve design productivity, the electronic design automation industry developed the Property Specification Language.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In formal verification terms, a property is a factual statement about the expected or assumed behavior of another object.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Ideally, for a given HDL description, a property or properties can be proven true or false using formal mathematical methods.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In practical terms, many properties cannot be proven because they occupy an unbounded solution space.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] However, if provided a set of operating assumptions or constraints, a property checker can prove (or disprove) certain properties by narrowing the solution space.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The assertions do not model circuit activity, but capture and document the designer's intent in the HDL code.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In a simulation environment, the simulator evaluates all specified assertions, reporting the location and severity of any violations.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In a synthesis environment, the synthesis tool usually operates with the policy of halting synthesis upon any violation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Assertion based verification is still in its infancy, but is expected to become an integral part of the HDL design toolset.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] An HDL is grossly similar to a software programming language, but there are major differences.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Most programming languages are inherently procedural (single-threaded), with limited syntactical and semantic support to handle concurrency.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] HDLs, on the other hand, resemble concurrent programming languages in their ability to model multiple parallel processes (such as flip-flops and adders) that automatically execute independently of one another.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Any change to the process's input automatically triggers an update in the simulator's process stack.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Both programming languages and HDLs are processed by a compiler (often called a synthesizer in the HDL case), but with different goals.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] For HDLs, "compiling" refers to logic synthesis; the process of transforming the HDL code listing into a physically realizable gate netlist.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] On the other hand, a software compiler converts the source-code listing into a microprocessor-specific object code for execution on the target microprocessor.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] As HDLs and programming languages borrow concepts and features from each other, the boundary between them is becoming less distinct.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] However, pure HDLs are unsuitable for general purpose application software development, just as general-purpose programming languages are undesirable for modeling hardware.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Yet as electronic systems grow increasingly complex, and reconfigurable systems become increasingly common, there is growing desire in the industry for a single language that can perform some tasks of both hardware design and software programming.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] SystemC is an example of such—embedded system hardware can be modeled as non-detailed architectural blocks (black boxes with modeled signal inputs and output drivers).
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The target application is written in C or C++ and natively compiled for the host-development system; in contrast to targeting the embedded CPU, which requires host-simulation of the embedded CPU or an emulated CPU.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The high level of abstraction of SystemC models is well suited to early architecture exploration, as architectural modifications can be easily evaluated with little concern for signal-level implementation issues.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] However, the threading model used in SystemC relies on shared memory, causing the language not to handle parallel execution or low-level models well.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] In their level of abstraction, HDLs have been compared to assembly languages.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] There are attempts to raise the abstraction level of hardware design in order to reduce the complexity of programming in HDLs, creating a sub-field called *high-level synthesis*.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Companies such as Cadence, Synopsys and Agility Design Solutions are promoting SystemC as a way to combine high-level languages with concurrency models to allow faster design cycles for field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs) than is possible using traditional HDLs.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Approaches based on standard C or C++ (with libraries or other extensions allowing parallel programming) are found in the Catapult C tools from Mentor Graphics, and the Impulse C tools from Impulse Accelerated Technologies.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] A similar initiative from Intel is the use of Data Parallel C++, related to SYCL, as a high-level synthesis language.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] It is also possible to design hardware modules using MATLAB and Simulink using the MathWorks HDL Coder tool or DSP Builder for Intel FPGAs or Xilinx System Generator (XSG) from Xilinx.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] The two most widely used and well-supported HDL varieties used in industry are Verilog and VHDL.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Several projects exist for defining printed circuit board connectivity using language based, textual-entry methods.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] Among these, new approaches have emerged that focus on enhancing readability, reusability, and validation.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] These modern methodologies employ open-source design languages specifically tailored for electronics, adopting declarative markup to specify what circuits should achieve.
[src:systemverilog/hardware-description-language] This shift integrates software development principles into hardware design, streamlining the process and emphasizing automation, reuse, and validation.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:systemverilog/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Direct Programming Interface (**DPI**) allows direct inter language function calls between the SystemVerilog and Foreign language.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] The functions implemented in Foreign language can be called from SystemVerilog and such functions are called **Import** functions.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Similarly, functions implemented in SystemVerilog can be called from Foreign language (**C/C++ or System C**); such functions are called **Export** functions.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] DPIs allow transfer of data between two domains through function arguments and return.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] 1) Function Import:- A function implemented in Foreign language can be used in SystemVerilog by importing it.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] A Foreign language function used in SystemVerilog is called Imported function.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Imported function can have input, output, and inout arguments.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] An Imported function shall not free the memory allocated by SystemVerilog code nor expect SystemVerilog code to free memory allocated by Foreign code or (Foreign Compiler).
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] A call to an Imported task can result in suspension of the currently executing thread.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] This occurs when an Imported task calls an Exported task, and the Exported task executes a delay control, event control or wait statement.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Thus it is possible for an Imported task to be simultaneously active in multiple execution threads.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] An Imported function or task can be equip with special properties called pure or context.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] A function whose results solely depends on the value of its input arguments with no side effects is called Pure function.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Functions specified as Pure shall have no side effects, their results need to depend solely on the values of their input arguments.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] A Pure function call can be safely eliminated if its result is not needed or if its results for the same value of input arguments is available for reuse without needing to recalculate.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Read or Write anything in Environment Variable, Shared memory, Sockets etc.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Access any persistent data like Global or Static variable.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] An Imported task can never be declared Pure.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] An Imported task or function which calls "Exported" tasks or functions or accesses SystemVerilog data objects other than its actual arguments is called Context task or function.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] 1) A Context Imported task or function can access (read or write) any SystemVerilog data object by calling (PLI/VPI) or by calling Export task or function.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] Therefore, a call to Context task or function is a barrier for SystemVerilog compiler optimization.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog-dpi] SystemVerilog code can call Unix functions directly by importing them, with no need for a wrapper.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog started with the donation of the Superlog language to Accellera in 2002 by the startup company Co-Design Automation.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The bulk of the verification functionality is based on the OpenVera language donated by Synopsys.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In 2005, SystemVerilog was adopted as IEEE Standard 1800-2005.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In 2009, the standard was merged with the base Verilog (IEEE 1364-2005) standard, creating IEEE Standard 1800-2009.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The SystemVerilog standard was subsequently updated in 2012, 2017, and most recently in December 2023.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog for verification uses extensive object-oriented programming techniques and is more closely related to Java than Verilog.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] These constructs are generally not synthesizable.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The remainder of this article discusses the features of SystemVerilog not present in Verilog-2005.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] There are two types of data lifetime specified in SystemVerilog: static and automatic.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Automatic variables are created the moment program execution comes to the scope of the variable.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Static variables are created at the start of the program's execution and keep the same value during the entire program's lifespan, unless assigned a new value during execution.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Any variable that is declared inside a task or function without specifying type will be considered automatic.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] To specify that a variable is static place the "`static`" keyword in the declaration before the type, e.g., "`static int x;`".
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The "`automatic`" keyword is used in the same way.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Verilog-1995 and -2001 limit reg variables to behavioral statements such as RTL code.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog extends the reg type so it can be driven by a single driver such as gate or module.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog names this type "logic" to remind users that it has this extra capability and is not a hardware register.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The names "logic" and "reg" are interchangeable.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A signal with more than one driver (such as a tri-state buffer for general-purpose input/output) needs to be declared a net type such as "wire" so SystemVerilog can resolve the final value.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Classical Verilog permitted only one dimension to be declared to the left of the variable name.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog permits any number of such "packed" dimensions.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A variable of packed array type maps 1:1 onto an integer arithmetic quantity.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In the example above, each element of `my_pack` may be used in expressions as a six-bit integer.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The dimensions to the right of the name (32 in this case) are referred to as "unpacked" dimensions.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] As in Verilog-2001, any number of unpacked dimensions is permitted.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] As shown above, the designer can specify an underlying arithmetic type (`logic [2:0]` in this case) which is used to represent the enumeration value.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The meta-values X and Z can be used here, possibly to represent illegal states.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The built-in function `name()` returns an ASCII string for the current enumerated value, which is useful in validation and testing.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] As shown in this example, SystemVerilog also supports typedefs, as in C and C++.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog introduces three new procedural blocks intended to model hardware: `always_comb` (to model combinational logic), `always_ff` (for flip-flops), and `always_latch` (for latches).
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An HDL compiler or verification program can take extra steps to ensure that only the intended type of behavior occurs.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An `always_comb` block models combinational logic.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An `always_latch` block models level-sensitive latches.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Electronic design automation (EDA) tools can verify the design's intent by checking that the hardware model does not violate any block usage semantics.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] For example, the new blocks restrict assignment to a variable by allowing only one source, whereas Verilog's `always` block permitted assignment from multiple procedural sources.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] When performing arithmetic operations with static numeric literals in RTL code, it is important to explicitly specify the bit-width of constants to avoid unintended truncation, linting violations or synthesis issues.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] This is particularly critical in combinational and sequential logic blocks.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] When operands lack explicit bit specifications, simulators and synthesis tools may infer widths based on context or default to implementation-specific sizes, potentially causing data loss or unexpected behavior during simulation or hardware implementation.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] For small designs, the Verilog *port* compactly describes a module's connectivity with the surrounding environment.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] But major blocks within a large design hierarchy typically possess port counts in the thousands.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog introduces the concept of interfaces to both reduce the redundancy of port-name declarations between connected modules, as well as group and abstract related signals into a user-declared bundle.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An additional concept is *modport*, which shows the direction of logic connections.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The following verification features are typically not synthesizable, meaning they cannot be implemented in hardware based on HDL code.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Instead, they assist in the creation of extensible, flexible test benches.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The `string` data type represents a variable-length text string.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An associative array can be thought of as a binary search tree with a user-specified key type and data type.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The key implies an ordering; the elements of an associative array can be read out in lexicographic order.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Finally, a queue provides much of the functionality of the C++ STL deque type: elements can be added and removed from either end efficiently.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] These primitives allow the creation of complex data structures required for scoreboarding a large design.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog provides an object-oriented programming model.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In SystemVerilog, classes support a single-inheritance model, but may implement functionality similar to multiple-inheritance through the use of so-called "interface classes" (identical in concept to the `interface` feature of Java).
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Classes can be parameterized by type, providing the basic function of C++ templates.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] However, template specialization and function templates are not supported.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog's polymorphism features are similar to those of C++: the programmer may specifically write a `virtual` function to have a derived class gain control of the function.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] See virtual function for further information.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Encapsulation and data hiding is accomplished using the `local` and `protected` keywords, which must be applied to any item that is to be hidden.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] By default, all class properties are public.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Class instances are dynamically created with the `new` keyword.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A constructor denoted by `function new` can be defined.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog has automatic garbage collection, so there is no language facility to explicitly destroy instances created by the new operator.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Integer quantities, defined either in a class definition or as stand-alone variables in some lexical scope, can be assigned random values based on a set of constraints.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] This feature is useful for creating randomized scenarios for verification.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Within class definitions, the `rand` and `randc` modifiers signal variables that are to undergo randomization.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] `randc` specifies permutation-based randomization, where a variable will take on all possible values once before any value is repeated.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Variables without modifiers are not randomized.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In this example, the `fcs` field is not randomized; in practice it will be computed with a CRC generator, and the `fcs_corrupt` field used to corrupt it to inject FCS errors.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The two constraints shown are applicable to conforming Ethernet frames.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Constraints may be selectively enabled; this feature would be required in the example above to generate corrupt frames.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Constraints may be arbitrarily complex, involving interrelationships among variables, implications, and iteration.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The SystemVerilog constraint solver is required to find a solution if one exists, but makes no guarantees as to the time it will require to do so as this is in general an NP-hard problem (boolean satisfiability).
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In each SystemVerilog class there are 3 predefined methods for randomization: pre_randomize, randomize and post_randomize.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The randomize method is called by the user for randomization of the class variables.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The pre_randomize method is called by the randomize method before the randomization and the post_randomize method is called by the randomize method after randomization.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The constraint_mode() and the random_mode() methods are used to control the randomization. constraint_mode() is used to turn a specific constraint on and off and the random_mode is used to turn a randomization of a specific variable on or off.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Assertions are useful for verifying properties of a design that manifest themselves after a specific condition or state is reached.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog has its own assertion specification language, similar to Property Specification Language.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The subset of SystemVerilog language constructs that serves assertion is commonly called SystemVerilog Assertion or SVA.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog assertions are built from **sequences** and **properties**.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Properties are a superset of sequences; any sequence may be used as if it were a property, although this is not typically useful.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Sequences consist of boolean expressions augmented with temporal operators.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] This sequence matches if the `gnt` signal goes high one clock cycle after `req` goes high.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Note that all sequence operations are synchronous to a clock.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Other sequential operators include repetition operators, as well as various conjunctions.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] These operators allow the designer to express complex relationships among design components.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An assertion works by continually attempting to evaluate a sequence or property.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An assertion fails if the property fails.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The sequence above will fail whenever `req` is low.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] This example shows an **implication** operator `|=>`.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The clause to the left of the implication is called the **antecedent** and the clause to the right is called the **consequent**.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Evaluation of an implication starts through repeated attempts to evaluate the antecedent.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] When the antecedent succeeds, the consequent is attempted, and the success of the assertion depends on the success of the consequent.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In this example, the consequent won't be attempted until `req` goes high, after which the property will fail if `gnt` is not high on the following clock.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In addition to assertions, SystemVerilog supports assumptions and coverage of properties.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An assumption establishes a condition that a formal logic proving tool must assume to be true.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] An assertion specifies a property that must be proven true.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In simulation, both assertions and assumptions are verified against test stimuli.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Property coverage allows the verification engineer to verify that assertions are accurately monitoring the design.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A SystemVerilog coverage group creates a database of "bins" that store a histogram of values of an associated variable.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Cross-coverage can also be defined, which creates a histogram representing the Cartesian product of multiple variables.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A sampling event controls when a sample is taken.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The sampling event can be a Verilog event, the entry or exit of a block of code, or a call to the `sample` method of the coverage group.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Care is required to ensure that data are sampled only when meaningful.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In this example, the verification engineer is interested in the distribution of broadcast and unicast frames, the size/f_type field and the payload size.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The ranges in the payload size coverpoint reflect the interesting corner cases, including minimum and maximum size frames.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] A complex test environment consists of reusable verification components that must communicate with one another.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Verilog's 'event' primitive allowed different blocks of procedural statements to trigger each other, but enforcing thread synchronization was up to the programmer's (clever) usage.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] SystemVerilog offers two primitives specifically for interthread synchronization: *mailbox* and *semaphore*.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The mailbox is modeled as a FIFO message queue.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Optionally, the FIFO can be type-parameterized so that only objects of the specified type may be passed through it.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Typically, objects are class instances representing *transactions*: elementary operations (for example, sending a frame) that are executed by the verification components.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The semaphore is modeled as a counting semaphore.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In addition to the new features above, SystemVerilog enhances the usability of Verilog's existing language features.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Besides this, SystemVerilog allows convenient interface to foreign languages (like C/C++), by SystemVerilog DPI (Direct Programming Interface).
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In the design verification role, SystemVerilog is widely used in the chip-design industry.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] The three largest EDA vendors (Cadence Design Systems, Mentor Graphics, Synopsys) have incorporated SystemVerilog into their mixed-language HDL simulators.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Although no simulator can yet claim support for the entire SystemVerilog Language Reference Manual, making testbench interoperability a challenge, efforts to promote cross-vendor compatibility are underway.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In 2008, Cadence and Mentor released the Open Verification Methodology, an open-source class-library and usage-framework to facilitate the development of re-usable testbenches and canned verification-IP.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Synopsys, which had been the first to publish a SystemVerilog class-library (VMM), subsequently responded by opening its proprietary VMM to the general public.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Many third-party providers have announced or already released SystemVerilog verification IP.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] In the design synthesis role (transformation of a hardware-design description into a gate-netlist), SystemVerilog adoption has been slow.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Many design teams use design flows which involve multiple tools from different vendors.
[src:systemverilog/systemverilog] Most design teams cannot migrate to SystemVerilog RTL-design until their entire front-end tool suite (linters, formal verification and automated test structure generators) support a common language subset.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In 2009, the Verilog standard (IEEE 1364-2005) was merged into the SystemVerilog standard, creating IEEE Standard 1800-2009.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Since then, Verilog has been officially part of the SystemVerilog language.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The current version is IEEE standard 1800-2023.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Hardware description languages such as Verilog use software-like syntax, but unlike software programming languages they model physical hardware, including concurrent operation, signal timing, and electrical behavior.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] There are two types of assignment operators; a blocking assignment (=), and a non-blocking (<=) assignment.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The non-blocking assignment allows designers to describe a state-machine update without needing to declare and use temporary storage variables.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Since these concepts are part of Verilog's language semantics, designers could quickly write descriptions of large circuits in a relatively compact and concise form.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] At the time of Verilog's introduction (1984), Verilog represented a tremendous productivity improvement for circuit designers who were already using graphical schematic capture software and specially written software programs to document and simulate electronic circuits.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The designers of Verilog wanted a language with syntax similar to the C programming language, which was already widely used in engineering software development.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Like C, Verilog is case-sensitive and has a basic preprocessor (though less sophisticated than that of ANSI C/C++).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Its control flow keywords (if/else, for, while, case, etc.) are equivalent, and its operator precedence is compatible with C.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Syntactic differences include: required bit-widths for variable declarations, demarcation of procedural blocks (Verilog uses begin/end instead of curly braces {}), and many other minor differences.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog requires that variables be given a definite size.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In C these sizes are inferred from the 'type' of the variable (for instance an integer type may be 32 bits).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A Verilog design consists of a hierarchy of modules.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Modules encapsulate *design hierarchy*, and communicate with other modules through a set of declared input, output, and bidirectional ports.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Internally, a module can contain any combination of the following: net/variable declarations (wire, reg, integer, etc.), concurrent and sequential statement blocks, and instances of other modules (sub-hierarchies).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Sequential statements are placed inside a begin/end block and executed in sequential order within the block.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] However, the blocks themselves are executed concurrently, making Verilog a dataflow language.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog's concept of 'wire' consists of both signal values (4-state: "1, 0, floating, undefined") and signal strengths (strong, weak, etc.).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This system allows abstract modeling of shared signal lines, where multiple sources drive a common net.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] When a wire has multiple drivers, the wire's (readable) value is resolved by a function of the source drivers and their strengths.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A subset of statements in the Verilog language are synthesizable.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog modules that conform to a synthesizable coding style, known as RTL (register-transfer level), can be physically realized by synthesis software.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Synthesis software algorithmically transforms the (abstract) Verilog source into a netlist, a logically equivalent description consisting only of elementary logic primitives (AND, OR, NOT, flip-flops, etc.) that are available in a specific FPGA or VLSI technology.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Further manipulations to the netlist ultimately lead to a circuit fabrication blueprint (such as a photo mask set for an ASIC or a bitstream file for an FPGA).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog was created by Prabhu Goel, Phil Moorby and Chi-Lai Huang between late 1983 and early 1984.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Chi-Lai Huang had earlier worked on a hardware description LALSD, a language developed by Professor S.Y.H.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The rights holder for this process, at the time proprietary, was "Automated Integrated Design Systems" (later renamed to Gateway Design Automation in 1985).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Gateway Design Automation was purchased by Cadence Design Systems in 1990.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Cadence now has full proprietary rights to Gateway's Verilog and the Verilog-XL, the HDL-simulator that would become the de facto standard (of Verilog logic simulators) for the next decade.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Originally, Verilog was only intended to describe and allow simulation; the automated synthesis of subsets of the language to physically realizable structures (gates etc.) was developed after the language had achieved widespread usage.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog is a portmanteau of the words "verification" and "logic".
[src:systemverilog/verilog] With the increasing success of VHDL at the time, Cadence decided to make the language available for open standardization.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Cadence transferred Verilog into the public domain under the Open Verilog International (OVI) (now known as Accellera) organization.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog was later submitted to IEEE and became IEEE Standard 1364-1995, commonly referred to as Verilog-95.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In the same time frame Cadence initiated the creation of Verilog-A to put standards support behind its analog simulator Spectre.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog-A was never intended to be a standalone language and is a subset of Verilog-AMS which encompassed Verilog-95.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Extensions to Verilog-95 were submitted back to IEEE to cover the deficiencies that users had found in the original Verilog standard.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] These extensions became IEEE Standard 1364-2001 known as Verilog-2001.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog-2001 is a significant upgrade from Verilog-95.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] First, it adds explicit support for (2's complement) signed nets and variables.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Previously, code authors had to perform signed operations using awkward bit-level manipulations (for example, the carry-out bit of a simple 8-bit addition required an explicit description of the Boolean algebra to determine its correct value).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The same function under Verilog-2001 can be more succinctly described by one of the built-in operators: +, -, /, *, >>>.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A generate–endgenerate construct (similar to VHDL's generate–endgenerate) allows Verilog-2001 to control instance and statement instantiation through normal decision operators (case–if–else).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Using generate–endgenerate, Verilog-2001 can instantiate an array of instances, with control over the connectivity of the individual instances.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] File I/O has been improved by several new system tasks.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] And finally, a few syntax additions were introduced to improve code readability (e.g. always @*, named parameter override, C-style function/task/module header declaration).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Verilog-2001 is the version of Verilog supported by the majority of commercial EDA software packages.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Not to be confused with SystemVerilog, *Verilog 2005* (IEEE Standard 1364-2005) consists of minor corrections, spec clarifications, and a few new language features (such as the uwire keyword).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A separate part of the Verilog standard, Verilog-AMS, attempts to integrate analog and mixed signal modeling with traditional Verilog.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The advent of hardware verification languages such as OpenVera, and Verisity's e language encouraged the development of Superlog by Co-Design Automation Inc (acquired by Synopsys).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The foundations of Superlog and Vera were donated to Accellera, which later became the IEEE standard P1800-2005: SystemVerilog.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] SystemVerilog is a superset of Verilog-2005, with many new features and capabilities to aid design verification and design modeling.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] As of 2009, the SystemVerilog and Verilog language standards were merged into SystemVerilog 2009 (IEEE Standard 1800-2009).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The `<=` operator in Verilog is another aspect of its being a hardware description language as opposed to a normal procedural language.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This is known as a "non-blocking" assignment.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Its action does not register until after the always block has executed.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This means that the order of the assignments is irrelevant and will produce the same result: flop1 and flop2 will swap values every clock.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The other assignment operator `=` is referred to as a blocking assignment.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] When `=` assignment is used, for the purposes of logic, the target variable is updated immediately.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In the above example, had the statements used the `=` blocking operator instead of `<=`, flop1 and flop2 would not have been swapped.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Instead, as in traditional programming, the compiler would understand to simply set flop1 equal to flop2 (and subsequently ignore the redundant logic to set flop2 equal to flop1).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The **always** clause above illustrates the other type of method of use, i.e. it executes whenever any of the entities in the list (the **b** or **e**) changes.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] When one of these changes, **a** is immediately assigned a new value, and due to the blocking assignment, *b* is assigned a new value afterward (taking into account the new value of **a**).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] After a delay of 5 time units, **c** is assigned the value of **b** and the value of **c ^ e** is tucked away in an invisible store.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Then after 6 more time units, **d** is assigned the value that was tucked away.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Signals that are driven from within a process (an initial or always block) must be of type **reg**.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Signals that are driven from outside a process must be of type **wire**.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The keyword **reg** does not necessarily imply a hardware register.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The definition of constants in Verilog supports the addition of a width parameter.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] There are several statements in Verilog that have no analog in real hardware, such as the $display command.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] However, the examples presented here are the classic (and limited) subset of the language that has a direct mapping to real gates.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The next interesting structure is a transparent latch; it will pass the input to the output when the gate signal is set for "pass-through", and captures the input and stores it upon transition of the gate signal to "hold".
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The output will remain stable regardless of the input signal while the gate is set to "hold".
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In the example below the "pass-through" level of the gate would be when the value of the if clause is true, i.e. gate = 1.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This is read "if gate is true, the din is fed to latch_out continuously." Once the if clause is false, the last value at latch_out will remain and is independent of the value of din.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The significant thing to notice in the example is the use of the non-blocking assignment.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A basic rule of thumb is to use **<=** when there is a **posedge** or **negedge** statement within the always clause.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A variant of the D-flop is one with an asynchronous reset; there is a convention that the reset state will be the first if clause within the statement.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The next variant is including both an asynchronous reset and asynchronous set condition; again the convention comes into play, i.e. the reset term is followed by the set term.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Note: If this model is used to model a Set/Reset flip flop then simulation errors can result.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Consider the following test sequence of events.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] 1) reset goes high 2) clk goes high 3) set goes high 4) clk goes high again 5) reset goes low followed by 6) set going low.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In this example the always @ statement would first execute when the rising edge of reset occurs which would place q to a value of 0.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The next time the always block executes would be the rising edge of clk which again would keep q at a value of 0.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The always block then executes when set goes high which because reset is high forces q to remain at 0.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This condition may or may not be correct depending on the actual flip flop.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] However, this is not the main problem with this model.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Notice that when reset goes low, that set is still high.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In a real flip flop this will cause the output to go to a 1.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] However, in this model it will not occur because the always block is triggered by rising edges of set and reset – not levels.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] A different approach may be necessary for set/reset flip flops.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The final basic variant is one that implements a D-flop with a mux feeding its input.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The mux has a d-input and feedback from the flop itself.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Note that there are no "initial" blocks mentioned in this description.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] There is a split between FPGA and ASIC synthesis tools on this structure.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] FPGA tools allow initial blocks where reg values are established instead of using a "reset" signal.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] ASIC synthesis tools don't support such a statement.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The reason is that an FPGA's initial state is something that is downloaded into the memory tables of the FPGA.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] An ASIC is an actual hardware implementation.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] There are two separate ways of declaring a Verilog process.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] These are the **always** and the **initial** keywords.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The **always** keyword indicates a free-running process.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The **initial** keyword indicates a process executes exactly once.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Both constructs begin execution at simulator time 0, and both execute until the end of the block.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Once an **always** block has reached its end, it is rescheduled (again).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] It is a common misconception to believe that an initial block will execute before an always block.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] In fact, it is better to think of the **initial**-block as a special-case of the **always**-block, one which terminates after it completes for the first time.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] These are the classic uses for these two keywords, but there are two significant additional uses.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The most common of these is an **always** keyword without the **@(...)** sensitivity list.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The **always** keyword acts similar to the C language construct **while(1) {..}** in the sense that it will execute forever.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The other interesting exception is the use of the **initial** keyword with the addition of the **forever** keyword.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The example below is functionally identical to the **always** example above.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The **fork/join** pair are used by Verilog to create parallel processes.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] All statements (or blocks) between a fork/join pair begin execution simultaneously upon execution flow hitting the **fork**.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Execution continues after the **join** upon completion of the longest running statement or block between the **fork** and **join**.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The way the above is written, it is possible to have either the sequences "ABC" or "BAC" print out.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The order of simulation between the first $write and the second $write depends on the simulator implementation, and may purposefully be randomized by the simulator.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This allows the simulation to contain both accidental race conditions as well as intentional non-deterministic behavior.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Notice that VHDL cannot dynamically spawn multiple processes like Verilog.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The order of execution is not always guaranteed within Verilog.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This can best be illustrated by a classic example.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Depending on the order of execution of the initial blocks, it could be zero and zero, or alternately zero and some other arbitrary uninitialized value.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The `$display` statement will always execute after both assignment blocks have completed, due to the #1 delay.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] Note: These operators are *not* shown in order of precedence.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The IEEE 1364 standard defines a four-valued logic with four states: 0, 1, Z (high impedance), and X (unknown logic value).
[src:systemverilog/verilog] For the competing VHDL, a dedicated standard for multi-valued logic exists as IEEE 1164 with nine levels.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] System tasks are available to handle simple I/O and various design measurement functions during simulation.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] All system tasks are prefixed with **$** to distinguish them from user tasks and functions.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] This section presents a short list of the most frequently used tasks.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The PLI provides a programmer with a mechanism to transfer control from Verilog to a program function written in C language.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] It is officially deprecated by IEEE Std 1364-2005 in favor of the newer Verilog Procedural Interface, which completely replaces the PLI.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] The PLI (now VPI) enables Verilog to cooperate with other programs written in the C language such as test harnesses, instruction set simulators of a microcontroller, debuggers, and so on.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] For example, it provides the C functions `tf_putlongp()` and `tf_getlongp()` which are used to write and read the 64-bit integer argument of the current Verilog task or function, respectively.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] For 32-bit integers, `tf_putp()` and `tf_getp()` are used.
[src:systemverilog/verilog] For information on Verilog simulators, see the list of Verilog simulators.
